### C2: OTP Generated with `Math.random()` — Not Cryptographically Secure

> **What:** [`otp.service.js:41`](file:///d:/Mallakhamb-Repo/Mallakhamb-server-refactor/Server/src/services/auth/otp.service.js#L41) generates OTP codes using `Math.random()`, which is predictable.
>
> **Why it matters:** An attacker who knows the approximate time the OTP was generated can narrow down the seed state and predict the OTP value. This is the password reset flow — predicting it means full account takeover.
>
> **Where:** [`otp.service.js`](file:///d:/Mallakhamb-Repo/Mallakhamb-server-refactor/Server/src/services/auth/otp.service.js) — `generateOTPCode()` method.

**Current code:**
```javascript
generateOTPCode() {
  const otpLength = this.config.get('security.otpLength');
  const max = Math.pow(10, otpLength) - 1;
  const min = Math.pow(10, otpLength - 1);
  const otp = Math.floor(Math.random() * (max - min + 1)) + min;
  return otp.toString();
}
```

**Fixed code:**
```javascript
const crypto = require('crypto'); // already imported at top

generateOTPCode() {
  const otpLength = this.config.get('security.otpLength');
  const max = Math.pow(10, otpLength);
  const min = Math.pow(10, otpLength - 1);
  const range = max - min;
  
  // Use crypto.randomInt for uniform, cryptographically secure random number
  const otp = crypto.randomInt(min, max);
  return otp.toString();
}
```

> Note: `crypto` is already imported in the file but the line is dead code.

