### H2: Inconsistent Role Naming — `superadmin` vs `super_admin`

> **What:** The codebase uses both `'superadmin'` and `'super_admin'` in different places, and the auth middleware tries to handle both.
>
> **Why it matters:** A subtle mismatch means authorization checks can silently fail. For example, a token issued with `userType: 'superadmin'` may bypass checks that only compare against `'super_admin'`.
>
> **Where:**
> - [`auth.middleware.js:233`](file:///d:/Mallakhamb-Repo/Mallakhamb-server-refactor/Server/src/middleware/auth.middleware.js#L233): `requireAdmin = requireRole('admin', 'superadmin', 'super_admin')`
> - [`auth.middleware.js:249`](file:///d:/Mallakhamb-Repo/Mallakhamb-server-refactor/Server/src/middleware/auth.middleware.js#L249): `req.userType === 'superadmin' || req.user.role === 'super_admin'`
> - Admin model enum: `['admin', 'super_admin']`
> - Routes: `/api/superadmin` and `/api/super-admin` both mount the same routes

**Fix:** Standardize on ONE value. Since the Admin model uses `'super_admin'`, adopt that everywhere:
```javascript
// auth.middleware.js
const requireAdmin = requireRole('admin', 'super_admin');
const requireSuperAdmin = requireRole('super_admin');

// routes/index.js — remove the duplicate mount
app.use('/api/super-admin', superAdminRoutes);
// app.use('/api/superadmin', superAdminRoutes);  // REMOVE
```

