### H5: Missing Password Hashing Guarantee on `updateById`

> **What:** [`authentication.service.js:301`](file:///d:/Mallakhamb-Repo/Mallakhamb-server-refactor/Server/src/services/auth/authentication.service.js#L301) calls `repository.updateById(user._id, { password: newPassword, ... })`, relying on the base repository to detect a password field and use `.save()` to trigger the pre-save hook.
>
> **Why it matters:** The [`base.repository.js`](file:///d:/Mallakhamb-Repo/Mallakhamb-server-refactor/Server/src/repositories/base.repository.js#L183-L195) does handle this case — but it's fragile. If anyone changes the `updateById` method or adds a new repository without this check, passwords could be stored in plaintext. This is a correctness concern with a wide blast radius.
>
> **Where:** [`base.repository.js:183-195`](file:///d:/Mallakhamb-Repo/Mallakhamb-server-refactor/Server/src/repositories/base.repository.js#L183-L195).
>
> **Fix:** Hash passwords at the service layer before passing to the repository:
```javascript
// authentication.service.js — resetPasswordWithOTP
const bcrypt = require('bcryptjs');
const hashedPassword = await bcrypt.hash(newPassword, 12);
await repository.updateById(user._id, {
  password: hashedPassword,
  resetPasswordToken: null,
  resetPasswordExpires: null
});
```

