## Architecture Assessment

### What's Good ✅

| Area | Assessment |
|------|-----------|
| **Layered Architecture** | Clean `route → controller → service → repository → model` chain |
| **DI Container** | Custom but solid, with circular dependency detection and singleton/transient lifecycles |
| **Error Hierarchy** | `BaseError → AuthenticationError, AuthorizationError, ValidationError, etc.` — well done |
| **Config Management** | Centralized with validation at startup, typed getters, environment-aware defaults |
| **Security Middleware Stack** | Helmet, mongoSanitize, rate limiting (IP + user + auth), CSRF, HTTPS enforcement |
| **Repository Pattern** | Base repository with soft delete, lean queries, password-aware updates |
| **Socket.IO Architecture** | Proper manager class with auth middleware, room management, metrics integration |
| **Graceful Shutdown** | Full handler for HTTP, WebSocket, DB, and metrics cleanup |

### What Needs Work ⚠️

| Area | Issue |
|------|-------|
| **`server.js` is a God File** | 200 lines doing config, CORS, body parsing, rate limiting, debug endpoints, and server startup. The refactored middleware in `security.middleware.js` exists but isn't wired in. |
| **`bootstrap.js` Manual Wiring** | 310 lines of manual DI registration. No auto-discovery, no module grouping. Adding a new service requires editing 3+ files. |
| **Socket Manager Late Injection** | `initializeSocketIO` mutates 5 already-resolved singletons by assigning `.socketManager`. This is a code smell — consider using lazy resolution or event-based initialization. |
| **No Input Validation on Password Reset** | `resetPasswordWithOTP` doesn't validate new password strength — the controller passes `req.body.password` directly with no strength check. |

